@article{Rousseau2020,
abstract = {Pulverized coal-fired power plants will remain a significant part of the electricity generation mix for years to come but should not restrict generation from clean renewable energy sources. Enhancing their flexibility is therefore crucial to achieving the required power system transformation. Predicting the furnace membrane wall temperatures is important in the study of flexible operation. This paper presents a new thermofluid network-based model for membrane walls of pulverized coal boiler furnaces to enable the study of power plant flexibility. The relevant thermal resistance formulations are derived together with the effective overall heat transfer coefficient. Detail results show that the model scales very well to different geometries and operating conditions that cover the full range of operation of typical sub- and supercritical pulverized coal boilers, including very low loads. The overall UA value is predicted to within 5{\%} of the benchmark CFD results for all the cases presented, except for the case of a very thick tube wall, while the predicted temperatures are all within 4{\%}. The results therefore provide confidence that the model can be applied with good accuracy over the full range of operating conditions and waterwall geometries for both sub- and supercritical boilers.},
